EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Sandy, a hybrid storm with both tropical and extra-tropical characteristics, brought high winds and coastal flooding to southern New England.  Easterly winds gusted to 50 to 60 mph for interior southern New England; 55 to 65 mph along the eastern Massachusetts coast and along the I-95 corridor in southeast Massachusetts and Rhode Island; and 70 to 80 mph along the southeast Massachusetts and Rhode Island coasts.  A few higher higher gusts occurred along the Rhode Island coast.  A severe thunderstorm embedded in an outer band associated with Sandy produced wind gusts to 90 mph and concentrated damage in Wareham early Tuesday evening, |a day after the center of Sandy had moved into New Jersey.  In general, moderate coastal flooding occurred along the Massachusetts coastline, and major coastal flooding impacted the Rhode Island coastline.  The storm surge was generally 2.5 to 4.5 feet along the east coast of Massachusetts, but peaked late Monday afternoon in between high tide cycles.  Seas built to between 20 and 25 feet Monday afternoon and evening just off the Massachusetts east coast.  Along the south coast, the storm surge was 4 to 6 feet and seas from 30 to a little over 35 feet were observed in the outer coastal waters.  The very large waves on top of the storm surge caused destructive coastal flooding along stretches of the Rhode Island exposed south coast.  ||Sandy grew into a hurricane over the southwest Caribbean and then headed north across Jamaica, Cuba, and the Bahamas.  As Sandy headed north of the Bahamas, the storm interacted with a vigorous weather system moving west to east across the United States and began to take on a hybrid structure.  Strong high pressure over southeast Canada helped with the expansion of the strong winds well north of the center of Sandy.  In essence, Sandy retained the structure of a hurricane near its center (until shortly before landfall) while taking on more of an extra-tropical cyclone configuration well away from the center.  Sandy���s track was unusual.  The storm headed northeast and then north across the western Atlantic and then sharply turned to the west to make landfall near Atlantic City, NJ during Monday evening.  Sandy subsequently weakened and moved west across southern Pennsylvania on Tuesday before turning north and heading across western New York state into Quebec during Tuesday night and Wednesday.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Automated Surface Observing System at Manchester-Boston Regional Airport (KMHT) recorded sustained wind speeds of 38 mph and gusts to 63 mph.  In Manchester, a tree was downed on Harrison Street.  In Hudson, a tree was downed on Lawrence Road, bringing down wires that sparked a fire that damaged a house.  In Merrimack, a tree was downed, taking down wires and closing Amherst Road from Meetinghouse Road to Riverside Drive.  In Nashua, a tree was downed onto a house on Broad Street, near the Hollils line.  No structural damage was found.  Numerous trees were downed, blocking roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several waves of low pressure moved south of southern New England bringing a prolonged period of snow to the region.  Anywhere from 1 to 12 inches of snow fell across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Seven to twelve inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County beginning February 29.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved up the coast over Southern New England from the mid-Atlantic. This brought a mixture of wintry precipitation and strong winds to the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to eight inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A rapidly intensifying low moved out of the mid-Atlantic, passing southeast of Southern New England.  This spread heavy snow across much of Southern New England, resulting in four to eight inches of snow across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals between four and eight inches were reported in the Nashua to Manchester corridor of eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of northwest Iowa in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The upper shortwave that pushed through the Southern Appalachians on the 16th, inducing the lee side trough, remained a factor in thunderstorm development on the 17th.  Additionally, a mid-level low off the Southeast Coast began moving onshore, bringing additional moisture to the area.  Numerous thunderstorms developed during the day, and several of them became severe with mostly wind damage, but a few large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Heard County 911 Center reported that several trees were blown down in the Centralhatchee area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level disturbance and associated cold front moved through the Mid-South during the evening hours of October 17, 2012. The cold front interacted with a moist and unstable airmass in place over the region and a line of showers and thunderstorms developed over Eastern Arkansas and then swept east across the Mid-South. Strong winds aloft aided in the development of the line of thunderstorms some of which became severe and produced large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Straight line winds knocked a tree onto a house in Rena Lara.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown onto a house in Tremont.  Several power lines were knocked down around town as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm that brought blizzard conditions to portions of Wisconsin and Minnesota and severe weather to portions of the Tennessee River Valley on February 29th weakened as it moved across the Northeast on March 1st.||There were two rounds of snowfall that moved across the North Country, the first during the evening and overnight of February 29th and the second during the daylight hours of March 1st. The first round delivered widespread 1-3 inches across much of the Champlain Valley and eastern slopes of the Adirondacks. The second round delivered another 1-3 inches with some areas that witnessed 3 to 5 inches additional accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began in the evening hours of February 29th and continued through March 1st. Snowfall accumulations in March storm data.

A weak low pressure system moved southeast of southern New England, bringing snow to much of southern New England.  While most of the area received at least an inch of snow, a mesoscale band set up along the south coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island resulting in incredible snowfall rates.  Eight to twelve inches of snow fell along the coast with five to eight inches falling on Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur Radio operator reported 3 to 5 inches of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level ridge remained in place over the Southern Plains, with weak northwest flow continuing across the Southeast.  Left over outflow boundaries from convection on the 25th helped to focus development on the 26th.  Numerous thunderstorms developed, and several became severe with wind damage reported.  Damage was reported from lightning strikes as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A historic church, built in 1904, was completely destroyed by a lightning strike and resulting fire at 71 West Candler Street.  The church was the oldest in Winder and had recently undergone over $700,000 worth of restoration and renovation, with only $10,000 left of repairs to go before it was fully restored.  As it was, the historic church was worth millions.  Firefighters were able to contain the blaze to the church alone, although other homes along the block were evacuated as a precaution.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, despite this shortcoming of rain Washington County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent and moist westerly flow with embedded disturbances resulted in heavy snow for the mountains and significant snowfall accumulations for some lower elevation aras of esatern Utah.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals of 3 to 5inches were measured across the area. Additionally, wind gusts of 20 to 30 mph produced localized blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold air mass was gradually retreating from Arkansas on the 13th, but precipitation moved in from the west before the cold air could exit. In most parts of Arkansas, precipitation began as snow. Then, as warmer air moved in during the day, the snow changed to a mixture of sleet and freezing rain. This occurred during the morning in southern and central sections, and during the afternoon in the north. Finally, the wintry mix changed over to rain as warmer air continued to invade the state. This changeover occurred during the morning in the south, around midday in central sections, and during the afternoon or early evening in the north. Snowfall totals over the southern half of the state were well less than an inch. Over the northern half, most snow accumulations were in the 1 to 3 inch range. However, totals to 4 inches were reported in the higher elevations of Newton County south of Jasper, and in northern Baxter County. Freezing rain amounts ranged from a trace to around .10 inch.

A line of strong to severe storms raced across the Missouri Ozarks and produced several reports of severe winds and wind damage. There was a weak tornado that spun up along the squall line.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Small shed and two greenhouses were destroyed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As had been the case for a few days, the Southeast states remained on the northern periphery of weak upper level ridging on the 15th.  Ample moisture and warm temperatures, very summer-like in nature, allowed for enough instability to produce scattered thunderstorms especially across north Georgia.  A few of these thunderstorms were able to reach severe levels, with scattered reports of large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public called to report golf ball size hail fell for over ten minutes between 12:27 AM EDT to 12:39 AM EDT.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As had been the case for several days, the Southeast states remained on the northern periphery of weak upper level ridging on the 22nd. Ample moisture and warm temperatures, very summer-like in nature, allowed for enough instability to produce scattered thunderstorms especially across north Georgia. One of these thunderstorms was strong enough to blow a tree onto a car.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A WSB-TV news reporter confirmed that a large hardwood tree broke off at the ground level and fell on the roof of a car in the Hickory Walk Subdivision off Whitlock Avenue.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As had been the case for several days, the Southeast states remained on the northern periphery of weak upper level ridging on the 31st. Ample moisture and warm temperatures, very summer-like in nature, allowed for enough instability to produce scattered thunderstorms especially across north Georgia.  With the addition of an upper-level shortwave moving across the area, some of these storms became severe with multiple reports of large hail received.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported that dime sized hail fell for 10 minutes in northern Catoosa County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Mid-level ridge over the Southern Plains continued to decay on the 27th while a weak surface trough, mainly resulting from convection on the 26th, remained in place.  An upper trough began to push into the Tennessee Valley, providing additional upper-level support for convective development.  Numerous thunderstorms developed across the region, and several of them became severe with damaging winds reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Wilkinson County 911 Center reported numerous trees down in Toomsboro.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broken line of scattered thunderstorms developed across the Middle Red River Valley of Northeast Texas and Southwest Arkansas during the late night hours of October 13 and the predawn hours of October 14th. The thunderstorms developed in an unstable airmass and were preceded by a strong cold front in association with an upper level trough moving into the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley. Strong damaging wind gusts were the primary result with these thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and phone lines were downed in Clarksville and Bogota, Texas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An extended period of dry weather continued to worsen across central and southeast Illinois during the month of June...with most locations reporting monthly rainfall deficits of 2 to 4 inches.  Due to an abnormally warm and dry spring, yearly rainfall deficits since January 1st grew to as much as 5 to 10 inches in June.  The prolonged period of dry weather caused many locations along and south of I-72 to become classified in severe drought conditions (D2).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very warm and dry conditions developed across DeWitt County in June. Observers from Clinton to Farmer City reported only 0.50 to 1.50 of rain for the month. Farmer City had their 5th driest June on record. As a result, DeWitt County was designated as a Severe Drought area on June 19th. Local officials instituted a ban on open burning.

The prolonged period of dry weather caused many locations along and south of I-72 to become classified in severe drought conditions (D2).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very warm and dry conditions developed across Jasper County in June. The flow of the Embarras River at Ste. Marie was only in the 8th percentile during the last half of the month. As a result, Jasper County was designated as a Severe Drought area on June 19th. Local officials instituted a ban on open burning.

A winter weather advisory was issued for much of the area effective from 6am Monday December 31st through 6am Jan 1st.  Snow began to fall around 6am on December 1st and accumulated to between 5 and 7 inches across Cloud and Republic Counties.  The remainder of the area receive between 2 and 5 inches of snow.  Winds were not particularly strong and averaged 10 to 15 mph and visibilities also ranged from one half to one mile at most times during the snowfall.  However, the snow did accumulate to around 6 inches within 12 hours and thus those two counties will be listed as enduring heavy snow for this event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters and COOP observers measured between 5 and 7 inches of snow across Cloud and Republic Counties by Monday evening December 31st.  The snow began falling around 6 am that day and accumulated to around 6 inches around 12 hours later.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of December. December brought a small amount of moisture in the form of some snow during the middle part of the month, and again at the very end of the month. Although some moisture did arrive to the area, the drought persisted through the month with D2 to D3 conditions continuing through the month, and into January.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought persisted across Anderson County during the month of December. Although some moisture arrived to the area in the form of snow during the latter half of the month D2 to D3 conditions continued into January.

In most parts of Arkansas, precipitation began as snow. Then, as warmer air moved in during the day, the snow changed to a mixture of sleet and freezing rain. This occurred during the morning in southern and central sections, and during the afternoon in the north. Finally, the wintry mix changed over to rain as warmer air continued to invade the state. This changeover occurred during the morning in the south, around midday in central sections, and during the afternoon or early evening in the north. Snowfall totals over the southern half of the state were well less than an inch. Over the northern half, most snow accumulations were in the 1 to 3 inch range. However, totals to 4 inches were reported in the higher elevations of Newton County south of Jasper, and in northern Baxter County. Freezing rain amounts ranged from a trace to around .10 inch.

Snowfall totals over the southern half of the state were well less than an inch. Over the northern half, most snow accumulations were in the 1 to 3 inch range. However, totals to 4 inches were reported in the higher elevations of Newton County south of Jasper, and in northern Baxter County. Freezing rain amounts ranged from a trace to around .10 inch.

A broken pre-frontal line of thunderstorms moved across inland southeast Georgia during the evening where the airmass was moderately unstable. A short wave upper level trough moved over the low level front. The phasing of these convective ingredient ignited several severe storms across the Altamaha River basin which produced widespread hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Golfball size hail was reported 9 miles north of Baxley.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought periods of moderate to heavy snow to parts of the North Central Mountains, Front Range Foothills, Urban Corridor with blizzard conditions developing over the parts of the Northeast Plains of Colorado.  The combination of snow and wind reportedly reduced the visibilities to just a few hundred feet at times, and resulted in several road closures.  Across eastern Elbert, Lincoln, Logan, Phillips, Sedgwick and Washington Counties, gusty northerly winds ranged from 35 to 55 mph producing extensive blowing and drifting snow, ranging from 1 to 4 feet in depth.  Storm totals in those areas were difficult to measure but estimated to range from 3 to 5 inches.   ||Road closures included:  Interstate 70, east of Aurora to the Kansas Stateline; U.S. Highway 24, from Limon to Colorado Springs; Colorado Highway 94 between Punkin Center and Enoch; U.S. Highway 40/287 between Limon and Kit Carson; Colorado Highway 71 from east of Fort Morgan to Limon; U.S. Highway 34 from Brush to Yuma.||In the mountain and foothills, the heaviest amounts generally occurred north of Interstate 70.  Storm totals included:  13 inches at Estes Park, 12 inches at Genesee and Red Feather Lakes, 11 inches at Glen Haven; 10.5 inches at Livermore, 9 inches, 4 miles west-southwest of Eldorado Springs; 8.5 inches at Coal Creek Canyon and near Crescent Village; 8 inches near Evergreen, 7 inches at Drake and Bear Lake; with 6 inches at Eldora Ski Area, Idaho Springs, Grandby, Gross Reservoir and Nederland.|Along the Urban Corridor and adjacent plains, lesser storm totals from 1 to 4 inches were observed.

The surface and mid level pressure gradient tightened up in response to an approaching upper level trough west of the Texas Panhandle and a strong cold front which pushed through the Texas Panhandle during the morning hours. As a result, west and northwest non-thunderstorm gradient winds increased by the late morning and afternoon hours across all but the northeast Texas Panhandle. There were no reports of injuries or fatalities, however damage was reported across the south central Texas Panhandle.

An extended period of dry weather continued to worsen across central and southeast Illinois during the month of June...with most locations reporting monthly rainfall deficits of 2 to 4 inches.  Due to an abnormally warm and dry spring, yearly rainfall deficits since January 1st grew to as much as 5 to 10 inches in June.  The prolonged period of dry weather caused many locations along and south of I-72 to become classified in severe drought conditions (D2).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very warm and dry conditions developed in Lawrence County during June. Rain only occurred twice during the month at Lawrenceville, for a total of 0.09. This was the driest June on record. The flow of the Embarras River at Lawrenceville was only in the 10th percentile. The county was designated in a Severe Drought on June 19th, and an Extreme Drought on June 27th. Local officials instituted a ban on open burning.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An extended period of dry weather continued to worsen across central and southeast Illinois during the month of June...with most locations reporting monthly rainfall deficits of 2 to 4 inches. The prolonged period of dry weather caused many locations along and south of I-72 to become classified in severe drought conditions (D2).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very warm and dry conditions developed across Logan County in June. Rainfall in Lincoln only totaled 0.58 for the month, which was the 3rd driest June on record. As a result, Logan County was designated as a Severe Drought area on June 19th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough was digging into New Mexico with a 125+ knot jet streak moving into Western New Mexico. These strong upper level winds combined with a 992mb surface low over Eastern Colorado and a lee trough over Eastern New Mexico to create wind gusts over 60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad Pacific trough brought heavy snowfall to the eastern Uinta Mountains of northeast Utah.  The upper trough also brought to the region some of the coldest air of the season so far.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread snowfall accumulations of 12 to 21 inches were measured at or above the 7000 foot level.  Wind gusts of 20 to 30 mph produced localized blowing and drifting snow.  Traffic was severely hampered by this early season snowfall event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad Pacific trough brought snowfall to the higher elevations and to some lower elevation areas of northwest Colorado.  The upper trough also ushered into the region some of the coldest air of the season so far.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread snowfall accumulations of 12 to 17 inches were measured across the area, including 17 inches on Rabbit Ears Pass where the chain law was put into effect.  Wind gusts of 20 to 40 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved through Southeast Texas during Christmas Day with strong winds and small hail in storms along the boundary, strong gradient winds behind the boundary, and low tides caused by persistent strong north winds behind the front. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure system tracking northeast through the Ohio Valley brought accumulating snow and blowing snow to northwest Ohio on December 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to heavy snow fell on December 26th, with total snow accumulations ranging between 6 and 10 inches across the county. A trained spotter in Lima reported 9.5 inches of total snow accumulation. The falling snow combined with wind gusts in excess of 30 mph reduced visibilities to less than a quarter of a mile at times. This also resulted is significant blowing and drifting snow. Slide-offs and accidents were reported across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As had been the case for several days, the Southeast states remained on the northern periphery of weak upper level ridging on the 31st. Ample moisture and warm temperatures, very summer-like in nature, allowed for enough instability to produce scattered thunderstorms especially across north Georgia.  With the addition of an upper-level shortwave moving across the area, some of these storms became severe with multiple reports of large hail received.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quarter size hail in the Thompson Bridge Road area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front approached the state late in the day on the 8th, but high pressure was in control of the area ahead of the front.  High fire danger conditions were not anticipated due to relative humidities above 25 percent.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The National Forest Service reported that a human-caused wildfire labeled Cantrell Road burned 3.5 acres and resulted in $1,500 in damages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front pushed through the area on the 9th, and high pressure was in control of the area on the 10th.  Cool and dry conditions prevailed, though fuel moistures remained too high for high fire danger conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The National Forest Service reported that a human-caused wildfire labeled Campbell Mtn. burned 105 acres and resulted in $24,000 in damages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak upper ridge was in place across the region and was forecast to strengthen over the next few days.  High fire danger conditions were not expected since relative humidities were above 25 percent and fuel moistures were above 10 percent.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The National Forest Service reported that a human-caused wildfire labeled Browns Chapel burned 1.5 acres and resulted in $5,000 in damages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another shortwave aloft pushed through the area during the late morning and early afternoon of June 5th.  The wave helped to push a weak cold front through the state as well, which acted as a focusing mechanism for thunderstorm development.  Instability increased ahead of the front across central Georgia, and numerous thunderstorms were able to develop during the early afternoon.  Several of these thunderstorms became severe, with damaging winds and large hail reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Telfair County 911 Center reported that several trees and large limbs were blown down along State Highway 31 near Workmore Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Mid-level ridge over the Southern Plains continued to decay on the 27th while a weak surface trough, mainly resulting from convection on the 26th, remained in place.  An upper trough began to push into the Tennessee Valley, providing additional upper-level support for convective development.  Numerous thunderstorms developed across the region, and several of them became severe with damaging winds reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Fayette County 911 Center reported a couple of trees down on Highway 92.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An extended period of dry weather continued to worsen across central and southeast Illinois during the month of June...with most locations reporting monthly rainfall deficits of 2 to 4 inches.  Due to an abnormally warm and dry spring, yearly rainfall deficits since January 1st grew to as much as 5 to 10 inches in June.  The prolonged period of dry weather caused many locations along and south of I-72 to become classified in severe drought conditions (D2).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very warm and dry conditions developed across Tazewell County in June. While monthly rainfall was only about 1 inch below normal, yearly deficits since January 1st were between 6 and 8 inches.  The flow along the Mackinaw River at Green Valley dropped into the 11th percentile.  As a result, Tazewell County was designated as a Severe Drought area on June 19th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific trough and associated cold front brought heavy snow accumulations and strong winds to many mountain locations in western Colorado.

Even stronger wind gusts were measured at ridgetops, including 90 mph on Mount Abrahms.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued across McCurtain County in Southeast Oklahoma during the month of October. The Chicken Creek Wildfire began approximately 1630CST about thirteen miles south southwest of Lake Meredith or eighteen miles north of Amarillo in northeastern Potter county. The wildfire began on the extreme southern end of Lake Meredith National Recreation Area in the Rosita off-road vehicle area; the wildfire spread north toward southeastern Moore county and extreme southwestern Hutchinson county. The Texas Forest Service and the National Park Service reported that the wildfire consumed a measured two thousand two hundred and twenty-three acres using global positioning system equipment. It was determined that two thousand one hundred and two acres were consumed on National Park Service land and one hundred and twenty-one acres were consumed on private land. There were no damages or injuries reported, however the wildfire did threaten an oil field and cattle. There were also no structures threatened and there were no evacuations. The wildfire was contained around 1800CST on January 22 after a rekindle of the fire occurred on Sunday. The National Park Service, Potter County Fire Department, Borger Fire Department, Global Frontline Solutions, and the Texas Forest Service out of Lubbock responded to the wildfire. The wildfire is believed to have been human-caused and investigations are continuing.

The surface and mid level pressure gradient tightened up in response to an approaching upper level trough west of the Texas Panhandle and a strong cold front which pushed through the Texas Panhandle during the morning hours. As a result, west and northwest non-thunderstorm gradient winds increased by the late morning and afternoon hours across all but the northeast Texas Panhandle. There were no reports of injuries or fatalities, however damage was reported across the south central Texas Panhandle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread and persistent heavy rainfall along a stationary frontal boundary stretching across northeastern Oklahoma and southeastern Kansas resulted in five to eight inch rainfalls across the region from April 29th through May 1st. This heavy rainfall resulted in moderate flooding of the Neosho River near Commerce.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Neosho River near Commerce rose above its flood stage of 15 feet at 1:00 pm CDT on April 30th. This flood continued through May 4th, following a crest of 22.04 feet on May 2nd, which resulted in moderate flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snow showers in strong northwest winds behind a cold front produced bands of lake enhanced snow across western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, Garrett county Maryland, and eastern Ohio. The heaviest snow fell on the higher elevations of northern West Virginia, Garrett county Maryland and southwest Pennsylvania with 6 to 14 inches of snow with blowing snow reducing visibilities. A separate band of heavy snow dropped 6 to 10 inches of snow across Venango county Pennsylvania. Accumulations across the remainder of the region were from 2 to 5 inches. Also during the event snow squalls contributed to a 20 car pile-up on Interstate 80 west of Dubois. 14 passenger vehicles and 6 tractor trailers were involved, with 17 injuries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broken pre-frontal line of thunderstorms moved across inland southeast Georgia during the evening where the airmass was moderately unstable. A short wave upper level trough moved over the low level front. The phasing of these convective ingredient ignited several severe storms across the Altamaha River basin which produced widespread hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported at 17 North Osage Lane.

Increasing winds and drier air moving in with a cold front dissipated the fog before sunrise.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance moved through north Georgia during the morning of April 26.  Additional upper level disturbances pushed through the Southeast during the evening and overnight hours on the 26th.  Also, an area of surface low pressure moving through the Ohio Valley pushed a cold front into north Georgia late on Thursday.  Two waves of scattered thunderstorms developed, one in the morning and again in the early evening.  With each wave, one thunderstorm was able to reach severe levels, with both severe thunderstorms occurring in the town of Hiawassee in Towns county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quarter sized hail in Hiawassee.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure remained in control of the area both at the surface and aloft.  Dry relative humidities were prevalent across the area, though fuel moistures across north Georgia remained too high for dangerous fire weather conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: In addition to the extreme heat that was just beginning to let up on the 1st, a surface trough remained in place across central Georgia, providing a focus for numerous showers and thunderstorms to develop. Many of these became severe, with multiple reports of large hail and downed trees.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, despite this shortcoming of rain Clay County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) drought.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Concordia received slightly above normal precipitation during October, and as a result Cloud County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hurricane Sandy moved north off the Atlantic Coast and combined with a complex low pressure system and deepening trough over the eastern part of the U.S., and then turned west northwest and into New Jersey into Pennsylvania, slowing down and then drifting north. It produced an expansive area of high impact weather as it approached the coast and moved inland. Strong winds and heavy snowfall were the biggest impacts on southeastern West Virginia, northwestern North Carolina and extreme southwestern Virginia, lasting for 24-48 hours. One to two feet of snow with significant drifting was observed in the higher elevations, with a sharp reduction to little or no accumulation in the valleys. Winds gusted into the 50-60 mph range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds downed several large trees and power lines along Grapefield Road near Suiter. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm that brought blizzard conditions to portions of Wisconsin and Minnesota and severe weather to portions of the Tennessee River Valley on February 29th weakened as it moved across the Northeast on March 1st.||There were two rounds of snowfall that moved across the North Country, the first during the evening and overnight of February 29th and the second during the daylight hours of March 1st. The first round delivered widespread 1-3 inches across much of Vermont with 6 to 10 inches along the east slopes of the central and southern Green Mountains. The second round delivered another 1-3 inches with some areas that witnessed 3 to 5 inches additional accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began during the evening hours of February 29th and continued through March 1st. Snowfall accumulations are included in March storm data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak trough moved through southern California late on the 23rd into the morning of the 24th, providing another round of light to moderate precipitation, and strong winds in the mountains and desert slopes. Many locations gusted over 50 mph during the morning and early afternoon of the 24th. Another, deeper, trough dug south through the region and on the 26th into the morning of the 27th, bringing more strong, gusty winds to the mountains and desert slopes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds began at the Volcan Mountain SDGE mesonet between 0850 and 0900 PST on the 24th and ended between 1320 and 1330 PST the same day. During this time winds mostly gusted over 60 mph, with a peak gust of 70 mph between 1110 and 1120 PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) tracked east across northern Alabama during the early morning hours. Wind damage occurred in the western portions of the city of Madison in eastern Limestone County, and again along Governor's Drive in southeast Huntsville in Madison County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were knocked down at the intersection of Eastview Drive and Highland Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved across the Appalachians southeast of the Upper Ohio Valley and produce a mixed bag of heavy freezing rain, sleet and heavy snow across parts of the region. Freezing rain accumulations from one quarter to over one half inch occurred across eastern Ohio along Interstate 70 to southwest Pennsylvania, and extended south to the Mason Dixon line, and into Garrett county Maryland. North of this band heavy snow of 6 to 7 inches fell from New Philadelphia, Oh to Pittsburgh. Lighter snows of 3 to 6 inches fell from north of Pittsburgh to Interstate 80, and a small amount of freezing rain fell across portions of northern West Virginia.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another shortwave aloft pushed through the area during the late morning and early afternoon of June 5th.  The wave helped to push a weak cold front through the state as well, which acted as a focusing mechanism for thunderstorm development.  Instability increased ahead of the front across central Georgia, and numerous thunderstorms were able to develop during the early afternoon.  Several of these thunderstorms became severe, with damaging winds and large hail reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported that golf ball sized hail fell in Vidalia for about 15 minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hurricane Sandy moved north off the Atlantic Coast and combined with a complex low pressure system and deepening trough over the eastern part of the U.S., and then turned west northwest and into New Jersey into Pennsylvania, slowing down and then drifting north. It produced an expansive area of high impact weather as it approached the coast and moved inland. Strong winds and heavy snowfall were the biggest impacts on southeastern West Virginia, northwestern North Carolina and extreme southwestern Virginia, lasting for 24-48 hours. One to two feet of snow with significant drifting was observed in the higher elevations, with a sharp reduction to little or no accumulation in the valleys. Winds gusted into the 50-60 mph range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds blew a few trees down near Newport. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought continued to intensify and expand across parts of central and northeast South Dakota through October, resulting in severe to exceptional drought conditions. Many locations continued the trend of recording well below normal precipitation totals for the month. Exceptional drought conditions expanded into Stanley, Jones and southern Lyman counties. Extreme drought conditions spread into southern Dewey, Sully, Hughes, Lyman, Jones, southwest Hyde, Hamlin, Codington, Grant and Deuel counties. Severe drought conditions spread into Corson, Dewey, northwest Hyde, Hand, Faulk, Edmunds, McPherson, Brown, eastern Clark and southern Roberts counties.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, and as a result of this shortcoming of rain Geary County experienced a persistence in drought conditions as the county began and ended the month in D3 (extreme) drought.

High wildland fire danger, agricultural impacts and water shortages and restrictions were all being realized by the end of this month across many portions of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extreme drought conditions expanded across the majority of the northern Colorado mountains and adjacent plateaus.

While most of the area received at least an inch of snow, a mesoscale band set up along the south coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island resulting in incredible snowfall rates. Eight to twelve inches of snow fell along the coast with five to eight inches falling on Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur Radio operator reported 2 to 4 inches of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought periods of moderate to heavy snow to parts of the North Central Mountains, Front Range Foothills, Urban Corridor with blizzard conditions developing over the parts of the Northeast Plains of Colorado.  The combination of snow and wind reportedly reduced the visibilities to just a few hundred feet at times, and resulted in several road closures.  Across eastern Elbert, Lincoln, Logan, Phillips, Sedgwick and Washington Counties, gusty northerly winds ranged from 35 to 55 mph producing extensive blowing and drifting snow, ranging from 1 to 4 feet in depth.  Storm totals in those areas were difficult to measure but estimated to range from 3 to 5 inches.   ||Road closures included:  Interstate 70, east of Aurora to the Kansas Stateline; U.S. Highway 24, from Limon to Colorado Springs; Colorado Highway 94 between Punkin Center and Enoch; U.S. Highway 40/287 between Limon and Kit Carson; Colorado Highway 71 from east of Fort Morgan to Limon; U.S. Highway 34 from Brush to Yuma.||In the mountain and foothills, the heaviest amounts generally occurred north of Interstate 70.  Storm totals included:  13 inches at Estes Park, 12 inches at Genesee and Red Feather Lakes, 11 inches at Glen Haven; 10.5 inches at Livermore, 9 inches, 4 miles west-southwest of Eldorado Springs; 8.5 inches at Coal Creek Canyon and near Crescent Village; 8 inches near Evergreen, 7 inches at Drake and Bear Lake; with 6 inches at Eldora Ski Area, Idaho Springs, Grandby, Gross Reservoir and Nederland.|Along the Urban Corridor and adjacent plains, lesser storm totals from 1 to 4 inches were observed.

A low pressure system moved across the Appalachians southeast of the Upper Ohio Valley and produce a mixed bag of heavy freezing rain, sleet and heavy snow across parts of the region. Freezing rain accumulations from one quarter to over one half inch occurred across eastern Ohio along Interstate 70 to southwest Pennsylvania, and extended south to the Mason Dixon line, and into Garrett county Maryland. North of this band heavy snow of 6 to 7 inches fell from New Philadelphia, Oh to Pittsburgh. Lighter snows of 3 to 6 inches fell from north of Pittsburgh to Interstate 80, and a small amount of freezing rain fell across portions of northern West Virginia.

Low pressure moving across the Upper Ohio Valley produced rainfall of around an inch in 12 hours across the region. With saturated ground this was enough to bring streams and creeks out of their banks across northern Venango county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management reported numerous roads closed across the northern part of the county with streams and creeks out of their banks.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Showers and thunderstorms developed along the convergence of a cold frontal boundary and dry line.  This late season storm system was very vigorous for this late in the season.   Several discrete supercells and bowing line segments developed and produced reports of quarter sized hail and damaging wind gusts to 80 mph across portions of Central Kansas.

CZ_NAME: HAWK CHANNEL FROM WEST END OF SEVEN MILE BRIDGE TO HALFMOON SHOAL OUT TO THE REEF
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms in advance of a cold front produced gale-force wind gusts in the nearshore waters surrounding the Lower Florida Keys.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 35 knots was measured at Sand Key Light.

CZ_NAME: HAWK CHANNEL FROM WEST END OF SEVEN MILE BRIDGE TO HALFMOON SHOAL OUT TO THE REEF

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong wake low developed north and west of a vigorous squall line moving east through the Florida Straits.  High south and southwest winds developed across the Upper Florida Keys, producing isolated wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two trained spotters in Tavernier reported that strong south winds blew water completely out of canals on the Florida Bay side, causing numerous moored vessels to rest on the bay bottom.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong wake low developed north and west of a vigorous squall line moving east through the Florida Straits.  High south and southwest winds developed across the Upper Florida Keys, producing isolated wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree was blown over onto Harry Harris Drive in Tavernier, damaging power and water lines.  Limbs from the top of the tree caused minor damage to the roofing of two homes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Temperatures of 30 to 35 below zero combined with a north wind of 15 to 20 mph to produce wind chills as low as 63 below at the Holy Cross AWSS.  Wind chills of 60 below or lower were observed from approximately 0930AKST through 1300AKST on the 28th.

CZ_NAME: VOLUSIA-BREVARD COUNTY LINE TO SEBASTIAN INLET 0-20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance produced a line of thunderstorms which caused high winds along the Brevard County coastline and adjacent coastal waters.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 38 knot wind gust was measured at Patrick Air Force Base as a thunderstorm moved across the intracoastal waters and into the Atlantic.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms developed during the morning, along and in the wake of a warm front. Thunderstorms ended with the passage of an early afternoon pre-frontal trough.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down along Highway 53.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure system tracking northeast through the Ohio Valley brought accumulating snow and blowing snow to northwest Ohio on December 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow fell on December 26th, with total snow accumulations generally ranging between 1 and 3 inches across the county. The falling snow combined with wind gusts in excess of 30 mph reduced visibilities to less than a quarter of a mile at times. Temperatures were in the upper 20s as the snow fell which allowed roads to become snow covered and slick. This resulted in slide-offs and accidents across the region.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Small outbuildings were blown down and winds were estimated up to 70 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As had been the case for several days, the Southeast states remained on the northern periphery of weak upper level ridging on the 31st. Ample moisture and warm temperatures, very summer-like in nature, allowed for enough instability to produce scattered thunderstorms especially across north Georgia.  With the addition of an upper-level shortwave moving across the area, some of these storms became severe with multiple reports of large hail received.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quarter size hail off Brackett Ridge Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another shortwave aloft pushed through the area during the late morning and early afternoon of June 5th.  The wave helped to push a weak cold front through the state as well, which acted as a focusing mechanism for thunderstorm development.  Instability increased ahead of the front across central Georgia, and numerous thunderstorms were able to develop during the early afternoon.  Several of these thunderstorms became severe, with damaging winds and large hail reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Houston County 911 Center reported that a few trees and a few power lines were blown down, mainly in the vicinity of Elko Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front moved into north Georgia during the afternoon of Jun 13th, with moderate instability developing ahead of the front.  Numerous thunderstorms developed across mainly north Georgia during the afternoon, and a few of them became severe with large hail and downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported hail up to the size of quarters covering the ground near Pine Top Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Mid-level ridge over the Southern Plains continued to decay on the 27th while a weak surface trough, mainly resulting from convection on the 26th, remained in place.  An upper trough began to push into the Tennessee Valley, providing additional upper-level support for convective development.  Numerous thunderstorms developed across the region, and several of them became severe with damaging winds reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Newton County 911 Center relayed reports of a few trees down in far southern Newton County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought continued to intensify and expand across parts of central and northeast South Dakota through October, resulting in severe to exceptional drought conditions. Many locations continued the trend of recording well below normal precipitation totals for the month. Exceptional drought conditions expanded into Stanley, Jones and southern Lyman counties. Extreme drought conditions spread into southern Dewey, Sully, Hughes, Lyman, Jones, southwest Hyde, Hamlin, Codington, Grant and Deuel counties. Severe drought conditions spread into Corson, Dewey, northwest Hyde, Hand, Faulk, Edmunds, McPherson, Brown, eastern Clark and southern Roberts counties.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hurricane Sandy moved north off the Atlantic Coast and combined with a complex low pressure system and deepening trough over the eastern part of the U.S., and then turned west northwest and into New Jersey into Pennsylvania, slowing down and then drifting north. It produced an expansive area of high impact weather as it approached the coast and moved inland. Strong winds and heavy snowfall were the biggest impacts on southeastern West Virginia, northwestern North Carolina and extreme southwestern Virginia, lasting for 24-48 hours. One to two feet of snow with significant drifting was observed in the higher elevations, with a sharp reduction to little or no accumulation in the valleys. Winds gusted into the 50-60 mph range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds blew down two trees around Bedford and one tree near Northwood Heights. Damage values are estimated.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals of 8 to 15 inches were measured across the area. Additionally, wind gusts of 25 to 40 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow.

On October 13, 2012 scattered thunderstorms produced strong winds that caused some minor damage to areas in Cloud, Ottawa, and Marshall Counties. The extent of the damage were some power lines down in Minneapolis, Kansas and a couple large diameter tree branches down in Frankfort, Kansas.  A few 1 inch hail stones also fell in Cloud County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The sheriff reported a power line down from strong winds in Minneapolis.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large diameter tree branches were down near Frankfort.  The spotter in Frankfort reported 60 to 70 mph winds with the storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak low pressure system moved southeast of southern New England, bringing snow to much of southern New England.  While most of the area received at least an inch of snow, a mesoscale band set up along the south coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island resulting in incredible snowfall rates.  Eight to twelve inches of snow fell along the coast with five to eight inches falling on Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur Radio operator reported 9 to 10 inches of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Olive Wildfire in western Putnam county was burning since Nov. 24, 2011, north of State Road 20 just west of Interlachen and east of Melrose. As of Jan. 9th, the fire had burned about 1000 acres in the Levy Prairie. Smoke from the fire combined with fog to produce near zero visibilities at times. Several roads were closed in the area on the 8th and 9th, including portions of State Road 20 between County Roads 315 and 20A. Ochwilla Elementary had to be closed on the 9th due to smoke in the area, and opened late on the 10th due to smoke. Several auto accidents were blamed on poor visibilities in the vicinity of the fire on the 8th and the 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Olive wildfire continued to burn through January 2012, with most impacts reported on the 8th-10th. Smoke caused road closures, auto accidents, and the closing of a school.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wildfire burned about 41 acres on Cumberland Island.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Hickory Hill wildfire had burned about 41 acres on Cumberland Island.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broken pre-frontal line of thunderstorms moved across inland southeast Georgia during the evening where the airmass was moderately unstable. A short wave upper level trough moved over the low level front. The phasing of these convective ingredient ignited several severe storms across the Altamaha River basin which produced widespread hail.

A strong cold front moved through Southeast Texas during Christmas Day with strong winds and small hail in storms along the boundary, strong gradient winds behind the boundary, and low tides caused by persistent strong north winds behind the front. A reinforcing front moved through a couple of days later creating another low tide event along the coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong north winds behind a secondary cold front pushed the tide level down along the coast of Jefferson County. The tide level fell to 1.96 feet below the mean lower low water at 1639Z and this was 1.3 feet below the predicted level at low tide.

Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm that brought blizzard conditions to portions of Wisconsin and Minnesota and severe weather to portions of the Tennessee River Valley on February 29th weakened as it moved across the Northeast on March 1st.||There were two rounds of snowfall that moved across the North Country, the first during the evening and overnight of February 29th and the second during the daylight hours of March 1st. The first round delivered widespread 1-3 inches across much of Vermont with 6 to 10 inches along the east slopes of the central and southern Green Mountains. The second round delivered another 1-3 inches with some areas that witnessed 3 to 5 inches additional accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began during the evening hours of February 29th and continued through March 1st. Snowfall accumulations are included in March storm data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, and as a result of this shortcoming of rain Jackson County experienced a persistence in drought conditions as the county began and ended the month in D3 (extreme) drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hurricane Sandy moved north off the Atlantic Coast and combined with a complex low pressure system and deepening trough over the eastern part of the U.S., and then turned west northwest and into New Jersey into Pennsylvania, slowing down and then drifting north. It produced an expansive area of high impact weather as it approached the coast and moved inland. Strong winds and heavy snowfall were the biggest impacts on southeastern West Virginia, northwestern North Carolina and extreme southwestern Virginia, lasting for 24-48 hours. One to two feet of snow with significant drifting was observed in the higher elevations, with a sharp reduction to little or no accumulation in the valleys. Winds gusted into the 50-60 mph range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous large tree limbs were blown down across the county. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought continued to intensify and expand across parts of central and northeast South Dakota through October, resulting in severe to exceptional drought conditions. Many locations continued the trend of recording well below normal precipitation totals for the month. Exceptional drought conditions expanded into Stanley, Jones and southern Lyman counties. Extreme drought conditions spread into southern Dewey, Sully, Hughes, Lyman, Jones, southwest Hyde, Hamlin, Codington, Grant and Deuel counties. Severe drought conditions spread into Corson, Dewey, northwest Hyde, Hand, Faulk, Edmunds, McPherson, Brown, eastern Clark and southern Roberts counties.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The higher snowfall totals across the county include 8.0 inches at Friars Hill, 13.0 inches at Crawley, and 29.0 inches at Quinwood.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front across central Tennessee pushed into northwest Georgia on the afternoon of the 21st.  A series of upper level disturbances embedded within the northwest flow aloft helped convection to develop well ahead of the front.  Numerous strong thunderstorms developed, with several of them becoming severe with mainly large hail reported.  A couple of the storms produced wind damage in the form of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Jackson County Emergency Manager reported that several trees and power lines were blown down in and around the Nicholson area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface trough stretching from the Carolinas to east central Georgia interacted with an upper low moving across the Deep South on the afternoon of May 22.  Scattered thunderstorms developed, with several becoming strong.  Isolated storms became severe across central Georgia, with large hail and damaging winds reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A University of Georgia research agent reported that hail up to the size of dimes fell in southeastern Toombs County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary was the focus for scattered severe thunderstorms across portions of western Pennsylvania. A slow moving thunderstorm produced isolated flash flooding over Garrett county Maryland.

A stalled frontal boundary was the focus for scattered severe thunderstorms across portions of western Pennsylvania. A slow moving thunderstorm produced isolated flash flooding over Garrett county Maryland.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management reported trees and power lines down near Wampum.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved across southern New England resulting in gusty winds.  Some of these winds did some minor damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wires were downed on Easthampton Road by strong winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved across southern New England resulting in gusty winds.  Some of these winds did some minor damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed in Warren.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved up the coast over Southern New England from the mid-Atlantic. This brought a mixture of wintry precipitation and strong winds to the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to twelve inches of snow fell across Cheshire County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved up the coast over Southern New England from the mid-Atlantic. This brought a mixture of wintry precipitation and strong winds to the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five to twelve inches of snow fell across western and central Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Weak low pressure passing south of New England brought a wintry mix of precipitation to Massachusetts. Light freezing rain in northern Massachusetts resulted in a light coating of ice, with up to 1/4 inch of glaze reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around 1/4 inch of icing brought down tree limbs in Westminster and Shrewsbury.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A rapidly intensifying low moved out of the mid-Atlantic, passing southeast of Southern New England.  This spread heavy snow across much of Southern New England, resulting in six to twelve inches of snow across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals between 6 and 11 inches were reported in Hartford County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure ridged down the eastern slopes of the Appalachians on the 27th, allowing a cold air damming event to develop.  Fuels dried significantly during the day as relative humidities dropped in the cold dome, but relative humidities remained above the 25 percent threshold for fire danger conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The National Forest Service reported that a human-caused fire labeled Doublehead burned 3.8 acres and resulted in $1,500 in damages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level ridge strengthened over the area during the day on the 4th, suppressing most of the convection.  However, above-average temperatures continued, allowing instability to increase once again despite the influence of the ridge.  Isolated thunderstorms developed across eastern Georgia where the ridge had less influence, and spread west toward the Atlanta Metro area during the evening hours.  One thunderstorm became severe in Cobb County, with quarter-sized hail reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quarter sized hail from near Powder Springs to Pair Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front pushed into the state ahead of an upper level shortwave during the afternoon hours of April 17th, providing a focus for convection to develop.  Scattered strong thunderstorms developed across the area, with mainly small hail.  A few thunderstorms were able to increase to severe levels with both large hail and strong winds reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotters reported penny to quarter sized hail east to east-northeast of the Canton area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Lee Arrendale Correctional Center reported quarter sized hail in the area.  Additional reports of quarter sized hail were received from the public south of Baldwin.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of northwest Iowa in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered strong to severe thunderstorms occurred over the Mid-Coast region in the afternoon as an unstable air mass developed ahead of cold front. These storms moved east across San Antonio Bay and into the Gulf of Mexico.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: TCOON site at South Bird Island measured a wind gust to 35 knots.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold air mass was gradually retreating from Arkansas on the 13th, but precipitation moved in from the west before the cold air could exit. In most parts of Arkansas, precipitation began as snow. Then, as warmer air moved in during the day, the snow changed to a mixture of sleet and freezing rain. This occurred during the morning in southern and central sections, and during the afternoon in the north. Finally, the wintry mix changed over to rain as warmer air continued to invade the state. This changeover occurred during the morning in the south, around midday in central sections, and during the afternoon or early evening in the north. Snowfall totals over the southern half of the state were well less than an inch. Over the northern half, most snow accumulations were in the 1 to 3 inch range. However, totals to 4 inches were reported in the higher elevations of Newton County south of Jasper, and in northern Baxter County. Freezing rain amounts ranged from a trace to around .10 inch.
A prolonged period of heavy snow and strong winds impacted the Big Horn Mountains. Heavy snow and winds gusting to 65 mph created very dangerous conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Burgess Junction received 18 inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist, Pacific flow moved across the Billings Forecast Area. The moist flow overrunning a shallow arctic air mass resulted in heavy snow across the foothills locations of the Beartooth/Absaroka Mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 6 to 9 inches were reported in and around Red Lodge.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 7 to 9 inches along with bad road conditions were common around the Livingston area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of December. December brought a small amount of moisture in the form of some snow during the middle part of the month, and again at the very end of the month. Although some moisture did arrive to the area, the drought persisted through the month with D2 to D3 conditions continuing through the month, and into January.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought persisted across Jefferson County during the month of December. Although some moisture arrived to the area in the form of snow during the latter half of the month D2 to D3 conditions continued into January.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High winds were measured over the Northern Rocky Mountain Front as well as Central and Southwest Montana mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High wind gust of 35KT (40MPH) was reported 4 miles NNE of McAllister, MT at the Norris Hill DOT sensor.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High winds were measured over the Northern Rocky Mountain Front as well as Central and Southwest Montana mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High wind gust of 54KT (62MPH) was reported at the Heart Butte, MT RAWS.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High winds were measured over the Northern Rocky Mountain Front as well as Central and Southwest Montana mountains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous and quick hitting storm system brought heavy snow to the mountains of the Idaho Panhandle.  Snow fell as low as 3000 feet however the heaviest snow accumulations were at or above 4000 feet.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Bear Mountain SNOTEL observed twenty inches of snow.  Schweitzer Mountain Ski Resort reported fourteen inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong and wet winter storm consisting of deep isentropic ascent brought heavy snow to Northern Idaho Panhandle from the late afternoon on December 19th through midday on the 20th. The heaviest snow fell between the Coeur D Alene Area northward to the Canadian Border.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread snowfall amounts of six to twelve inches were reported across the Northern Idaho Panhandle with local amounts to fourteen inches noted at Schweitzer Ski Resort.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snow showers in strong northwest winds behind a cold front produced bands of lake enhanced snow across western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, Garrett county Maryland, and eastern Ohio. The heaviest snow fell on the higher elevations of northern West Virginia, Garrett county Maryland and southwest Pennsylvania with 6 to 14 inches of snow with blowing snow reducing visibilities. A separate band of heavy snow dropped 6 to 10 inches of snow across Venango county Pennsylvania. Accumulations across the remainder of the region were from 2 to 5 inches. Also during the event snow squalls contributed to a 20 car pile-up on Interstate 80 west of Dubois. 14 passenger vehicles and 6 tractor trailers were involved, with 17 injuries.

Strong mid level winds at the base of a passing upper trough resulted in high winds in the Guadalupe Mountains.  A cold front then moved south through the region and resulted in strong northeast winds in Guadalupe Pass.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong west winds continued for several hours early on the 9th at the Pine Springs Mesonet site with sustained speeds of 40-45 mph and gusts as high as 58 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong mid level winds at the base of a passing upper trough resulted in high winds in the Guadalupe Mountains.  A cold front then moved south through the region and resulted in strong northeast winds in Guadalupe Pass.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained northeast winds of 40-45 mph occurred for a couple of hours in Guadalupe Pass behind a strong cold front.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The passage of another upper trough just north of the region resulted in high winds in the Guadalupe Mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The passage of an upper trough just north of the region imparted high winds to the Guadalupe Mountains.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Higher elevations of the Guadalupe Mountains had several hours of high winds due to a passing upper level trough.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Guadalupe Pass had strong westerly winds due to an upper trough passing by just north of the area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong west winds of 40-50 mph sustained lasted much of the day in Guadalupe Pass with gusts as high as 68 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The passing of an upper level trough to the north of the region resulted in high winds across Southeast New Mexico.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained westerly winds of 40-53 mph and gusts over 60 mph occurred across portions of the Southeast New Mexico Plains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The passing of an upper level trough to the north of the region resulted in high winds across West Texas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong westerly winds of 40-50 mph sustained and gusts over 80 mph affected the Guadalupe Mountains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary was the focus for scattered severe thunderstorms across portions of western Pennsylvania. A slow moving thunderstorm produced isolated flash flooding over Garrett county Maryland.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management reported several trees down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A rapidly intensifying low moved out of the mid-Atlantic, passing southeast of Southern New England.  This spread heavy snow across much of Southern New England, resulting in six to twelve inches of snow across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals between eight and twelve inches were reported in Windham County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak low pressure system moved southeast of southern New England, bringing snow to much of southern New England.  While most of the area received at least an inch of snow, a mesoscale band set up along the south coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island resulting in incredible snowfall rates.  Eight to twelve inches of snow fell along the coast with five to eight inches falling on Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur Radio operator reported 5 to 8 inches of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of upper level disturbances moved through the Southeast from the 22nd into the 23rd, rotating around the mid-level low pressure system located near the Great Lakes.  These disturbances combined with increasing low level moisture and moderate instability as a result of southerly flow around a surface high located in the western Atlantic.  Strong to severe thunderstorms moved into northwest Georgia from northeast Alabama on Wednesday evening, and moved across north Georgia through midnight.  An EF-1 tornado touched down in Floyd County just east of Rome.  Isolated reports of large hail were received as the storms moved across north Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported that nickel to quarter size hail occurred for approximately ten minutes in the Oakwood area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level low pressure system moved across the Upper Mississippi Valley toward the Great Lakes on Friday, February 24.  An associated surface low that tracked up the Ohio Valley pushed a cold front through the Lower Mississippi Valley and into the Deep South.  Along and ahead of this front, several strong to severe thunderstorms developed in west central Georgia on Friday morning.  Scattered reports of large hail and wind damage were received as these storms moved across northern portions of central Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Troup County 911 Center reported nickel to golfball size hail occurring from near West Point to southeast of LaGrange.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave moved across northern Alabama during the late morning hours on May 29, pushing into northwest Georgia during the evening.  Meanwhile the remnants of Tropical Storm Beryl moved across southeast Georgia.  Instability was able to increase around the periphery of Beryl where cloud cover was not as thick, and as the shortwave moved into the state, isolated severe thunderstorms developed.  Most of the reports consisted of downed trees, but there was one report of severe hail as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Chattooga County 911 Center relayed reports of several downed trees and power lines in Lyerly.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front and a shortwave aloft pushed into the state during the evening of May 31st.  Numerous thunderstorms developed across the area, and several thunderstorms became severe.  Most of the severe reports consisted of downed trees, but there were a couple of large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Jefferson County 911 Center reported that three trees were blown down on the southeast side of Louisville.  One tree fell on power lines along Moore Street, and two additional trees fell along U.S. Highway 1.
