EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The upper shortwave that pushed through the Southern Appalachians on the 16th, inducing the lee side trough, remained a factor in thunderstorm development on the 17th.  Additionally, a mid-level low off the Southeast Coast began moving onshore, bringing additional moisture to the area.  Numerous thunderstorms developed during the day, and several of them became severe with mostly wind damage, but a few large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Henry County 911 Center relayed reports of quarter sized hail northeast of McDonough.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snow, accompanied by generally light winds, accumulated 3 to 5 inches during the daytime hours on December 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches, with the heavier accumulations in the northwest part of Brookings County. Winds were generally light during the snowfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 1 to 4 inches on December 8th over part of southwest Minnesota was followed by strong northwest winds gusting as high as 54 mph over more of the area on December 9th. The combination of winds, and loose snow cover from the previous day and earlier days, produced blizzard conditions on December 9th, reducing visibilities to near zero over large areas. Travel was curtailed or stopped, and business were closed for part of this weekend storm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Northwest winds gusting to 50 mph and loose snow cover combined to lower visibilities to near zero in blowing snow over much of the area. Travel was brought to a standstill and businesses were closed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hurricane Sandy moved north off the Atlantic Coast and combined with a complex low pressure system and deepening trough over the eastern part of the U.S., and then turned west northwest and into New Jersey into Pennsylvania, slowing down and then drifting north. It produced an expansive area of high impact weather as it approached the coast and moved inland. Strong winds and heavy snowfall were the biggest impacts on southeastern West Virginia, northwestern North Carolina and extreme southwestern Virginia, lasting for 24-48 hours. One to two feet of snow with significant drifting was observed in the higher elevations, with a sharp reduction to little or no accumulation in the valleys. Winds gusted into the 50-60 mph range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds blew several trees down in the county. Most of these trees fell in the Rainelle area. Another tree fell on a home in the 200 block of Matthews Road in Buckingham Acres near Lewisburg. Damage values are estimated.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A total of four trees were blown down in the county. Specifically, one was downed near Sandstone, two near Griffith Creek, and one near Suck Creek. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep layer southeast wind increased the moisture over northern Arizona during the day on July 12th. Strong thunderstorms produced heavy rain over the Western Mogollon Rim near the town of Williams.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotters reported 1.17 and 1.70 inches of rain in Williams.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist northwest flow aloft resulted in significant snowfall in many mountain areas and some lower elevation zones in western Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall accumulations around 3 inches were measured across most of the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist northwest flow aloft resulted in significant snowfall in many mountain areas and some lower elevation zones in western Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall accumulations of 3 to 6 inches were measured across the area.  Locally higher amounts included 9 inches in the Glenwood Springs area and in Glenwood Canyon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, despite this shortcoming of rain Marshall County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm produced a wind gust of 69 MPH four miles north of Prescott.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought continued to intensify and expand across parts of central and northeast South Dakota through October, resulting in severe to exceptional drought conditions. Many locations continued the trend of recording well below normal precipitation totals for the month. Exceptional drought conditions expanded into Stanley, Jones and southern Lyman counties. Extreme drought conditions spread into southern Dewey, Sully, Hughes, Lyman, Jones, southwest Hyde, Hamlin, Codington, Grant and Deuel counties. Severe drought conditions spread into Corson, Dewey, northwest Hyde, Hand, Faulk, Edmunds, McPherson, Brown, eastern Clark and southern Roberts counties.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hurricane Sandy moved north off the Atlantic Coast and combined with a complex low pressure system and deepening trough over the eastern part of the U.S., and then turned west northwest and into New Jersey into Pennsylvania, slowing down and then drifting north. It produced an expansive area of high impact weather as it approached the coast and moved inland. Strong winds and heavy snowfall were the biggest impacts on southeastern West Virginia, northwestern North Carolina and extreme southwestern Virginia, lasting for 24-48 hours. One to two feet of snow with significant drifting was observed in the higher elevations, with a sharp reduction to little or no accumulation in the valleys. Winds gusted into the 50-60 mph range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Higher snowfall totals across the county include 9.5 inches at Athens, 11.0 inches at Bluefield, 12.0 inches at Lashmeet, 15.0 inches at Princeton, and 28.0 inches at Flat Top.

Scattered thunderstorms developed, with several becoming strong.  Isolated storms became severe across central Georgia, with large hail and damaging winds reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Cherokee County Emergency Manager reported that a house was struck by lightning just south of Holly Springs.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak short waved moved through the Southern Appalachians into north Georgia the afternoon of the 16th, inducing the formation of a lee side trough.  The trough provided a focus for thunderstorm development during the afternoon and evening hours.  Several thunderstorms did develop, and one became severe, producing wind damage.  Lightning from other thunderstorms also caused fire damage as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Monroe County Emergency Manager reported that a barn was destroyed by lightning.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A rapidly intensifying low moved out of the mid-Atlantic, passing southeast of Southern New England.  This spread heavy snow across much of Southern New England, resulting in six to twelve inches of snow across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals between eight and eleven inches were reported in Tolland County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak low pressure system moved southeast of southern New England, bringing snow to much of southern New England.  While most of the area received at least an inch of snow, a mesoscale band set up along the south coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island resulting in incredible snowfall rates.  Eight to twelve inches of snow fell along the coast with five to eight inches falling on Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur Radio operator reported 8 to 9 inches of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved across the Appalachians southeast of the Upper Ohio Valley and produce a mixed bag of heavy freezing rain, sleet and heavy snow across parts of the region. Freezing rain accumulations from one quarter to over one half inch occurred across eastern Ohio along Interstate 70 to southwest Pennsylvania, and extended south to the Mason Dixon line, and into Garrett county Maryland. North of this band heavy snow of 6 to 7 inches fell from New Philadelphia, Oh to Pittsburgh. Lighter snows of 3 to 6 inches fell from north of Pittsburgh to Interstate 80, and a small amount of freezing rain fell across portions of northern West Virginia.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level low pressure system moved across the Upper Mississippi Valley toward the Great Lakes on Friday, February 24.  An associated surface low that tracked up the Ohio Valley pushed a cold front through the Lower Mississippi Valley and into the Deep South.  Along and ahead of this front, several strong to severe thunderstorms developed in west central Georgia on Friday morning.  Scattered reports of large hail and wind damage were received as these storms moved across northern portions of central Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported that golf ball sized hail fell just north of Jewell.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave moved across northern Alabama during the late morning hours on May 29, pushing into northwest Georgia during the evening.  Meanwhile the remnants of Tropical Storm Beryl moved across southeast Georgia.  Instability was able to increase around the periphery of Beryl where cloud cover was not as thick, and as the shortwave moved into the state, isolated severe thunderstorms developed.  Most of the reports consisted of downed trees, but there was one report of severe hail as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Bartow County 911 Center relayed reports of several downed trees, with minor roof damage to a structure along East Church Street in Cartersville.

Numerous thunderstorms developed during the day, and several of them became severe with mostly wind damage, but a few large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Dooly County Emergency Manager reported that several power lines were blown down at the intersection of Cypress Avenue and Fullington Avenue in Pinehurst.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The mid-level low across the Southeast Coast drifted into south Georgia on the 18th, stalled, and began to dissipate.  This continued to bring tropical moisture into the area.  Much like the past couple of days, numerous thunderstorms developed during the afternoon but without the influence of the surface trough from the 17th that had dissipated, fewer storms were able to reach severe levels.  Those that did occurred over north Georgia and resulted in reports of wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Forsyth County Emergency Manager reported that seven to ten trees were blown down in the Old Keiths Bridge Road, Perry Road, and Truman Mountain Road area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm that brought blizzard conditions to portions of Wisconsin and Minnesota and severe weather to portions of the Tennessee River Valley on February 29th weakened as it moved across the Northeast on March 1st.||There were two rounds of snowfall that moved across the North Country, the first during the evening and overnight of February 29th and the second during the daylight hours of March 1st. The first round delivered widespread 1-3 inches across much of Vermont with 6 to 10 inches along the east slopes of the central and southern Green Mountains. The second round delivered another 1-3 inches with some areas that witnessed 3 to 5 inches additional accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began during the evening hours of February 29th and continued through March 1st. Snowfall accumulations are included in March storm data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of December. December brought a small amount of moisture in the form of some snow during the middle part of the month, and again at the very end of the month. Although some moisture did arrive to the area, the drought persisted through the month with D2 to D3 conditions continuing through the month, and into January.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought persisted across Pottawatomie County during the month of December. Although some moisture arrived to the area in the form of snow during the latter half of the month D2 to D3 conditions continued into January.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deepening low pressure tracking from Arkansas to West Virginia produced heavy snow and strong winds across southeast Illinois on December 26th.  Locations from Lawrence County southeastward into the Ohio River Valley received the most snow, with many areas measuring between 8 and 12 inches.  The Cooperative Weather Observer in Lawrenceville picked up 11 inches.  The snow combined with winds gusting between 35 and 40 mph to produce blizzard conditions across Lawrence County.  Three to five-foot snow drifts and visibility less than one quarter of a mile resulted in numerous road closures across the county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Blizzard conditions impacted Lawrence County during the early morning of December 26th.  The falling and blowing snow reduced visibilities to less than one quarter of a mile and led to the closure of numerous roads across the county.  The Lawrenceville Coooperative Weather Observer measured 11 inches of snow.  Some locations around the county had snow drifts as deep as 3 to 5 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 1 to 4 inches on December 8th over part of southwest Minnesota was followed by strong northwest winds gusting as high as 54 mph over more of the area on December 9th. The combination of winds, and loose snow cover from the previous day and earlier days, produced blizzard conditions on December 9th, reducing visibilities to near zero over large areas. Travel was curtailed or stopped, and business were closed for part of this weekend storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, despite this shortcoming of rain Morris County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Hurricane Sandy moved north off the Atlantic Coast and combined with a complex low pressure system and deepening trough over the eastern part of the U.S., and then turned west northwest and into New Jersey into Pennsylvania, slowing down and then drifting north. It produced an expansive area of high impact weather as it approached the coast and moved inland. Strong winds and heavy snowfall were the biggest impacts on southeastern West Virginia, northwestern North Carolina and extreme southwestern Virginia, lasting for 24-48 hours. One to two feet of snow with significant drifting was observed in the higher elevations, with a sharp reduction to little or no accumulation in the valleys. Winds gusted into the 50-60 mph range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds blew three trees down. Individually, they were in the area of Fairwood, Independence, and Reavistown. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought continued to intensify and expand across parts of central and northeast South Dakota through October, resulting in severe to exceptional drought conditions. Many locations continued the trend of recording well below normal precipitation totals for the month. Exceptional drought conditions expanded into Stanley, Jones and southern Lyman counties. Extreme drought conditions spread into southern Dewey, Sully, Hughes, Lyman, Jones, southwest Hyde, Hamlin, Codington, Grant and Deuel counties. Severe drought conditions spread into Corson, Dewey, northwest Hyde, Hand, Faulk, Edmunds, McPherson, Brown, eastern Clark and southern Roberts counties.

A weak short waved moved through the Southern Appalachians into north Georgia the afternoon of the 16th, inducing the formation of a lee side trough.  The trough provided a focus for thunderstorm development during the afternoon and evening hours.  Several thunderstorms did develop, and one became severe, producing wind damage.  Lightning from other thunderstorms also caused fire damage as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Walton County 911 Center reported that several trees and many power lines were blown down in the Social Circle area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The upper shortwave that pushed through the Southern Appalachians on the 16th, inducing the lee side trough, remained a factor in thunderstorm development on the 17th.  Additionally, a mid-level low off the Southeast Coast began moving onshore, bringing additional moisture to the area.  Numerous thunderstorms developed during the day, and several of them became severe with mostly wind damage, but a few large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quarter-sized hail northwest of Callaway Gardens.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak low pressure system moved southeast of southern New England, bringing snow to much of southern New England.  While most of the area received at least an inch of snow, a mesoscale band set up along the south coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island resulting in incredible snowfall rates.  Eight to twelve inches of snow fell along the coast with five to eight inches falling on Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur Radio operator reported 6 to 7 inches of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved across the Tennessee Valley and into the Appalachians Friday Night through Saturday, December 29th and snow overspread the Ohio Valley. The heaviest snow generally fell along and southeast of Interstate 71, where 4 to 5 inches of accumulation was common. Northwest of the interstate, snowfall amounts were in the 2 to 4 inch range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A spotter in Chuckery measured 4.6 inches of snow. The county garage 3 miles northeast of Lafayette measured 3 inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of upper level disturbances moved through the Southeast from the 22nd into the 23rd, rotating around the mid-level low pressure system located near the Great Lakes.  These disturbances combined with increasing low level moisture and moderate instability as a result of southerly flow around a surface high located in the western Atlantic.  Strong to severe thunderstorms moved into northwest Georgia from northeast Alabama on Wednesday evening, and moved across north Georgia through midnight.  An EF-1 tornado touched down in Floyd County just east of Rome.  Isolated reports of large hail were received as the storms moved across north Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Jackson County 911 Center reported a house fire sparked by lightning outside of Commerce.  The house was an old Victorian home that had been converted into apartments.  Seven residents escaped without injury, but the house was heavily damaged.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snow spread over northwest Wisconsin on New Years Eve.  Most snow totals were less than 6 inches.  However, there were 6 to 7 inches of snow in far southern Sawyer County overnight on New Years Eve.  Lake-enhanced system snow brought 8 to 20 inches of snow to the snow-belt area of northern Wisconsin in a 36 hour period.  Specific amounts included 7 inches in Glidden, 10 inches in Montreal and Saxon and about 20 inches in Gile.

A strong storm system translated from the Pacific Northwest across the Southern Rockies and into the Southern Plains from the 23rd through the 25th. Rain began across west central Arkansas during the early morning hours of the 25th as this system approached and then transitioned to light freezing rain and a little sleet. The precipitation changed over to snow during the early afternoon of the 25th and fell heavily for several hours before tapering off late in the evening. A swath of heavy snow from four to six inches occurred across west central Arkansas.

A strong and wet winter system brought widespread moderate to heavy snow to much of the Inland northwest late afternoon December 19th through midday on the 20th.  The heaviest snow fell along and north of the Highway 2 corridor where numerous valleys picked up between four and eight inches.  The mountains saw between eight and fourteen inches.  The most impressive amount came from Holden Village located near the crest of the Northern Cascades, which received 24 inches of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous valley locations received between three and seven inches of snow through noon on December 20th.  Warmer air infiltrated the area around midday shifting the main threat for additional snow to elevations above 2000 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved across the Appalachians southeast of the Upper Ohio Valley and produce a mixed bag of heavy freezing rain, sleet and heavy snow across parts of the region. Freezing rain accumulations from one quarter to over one half inch occurred across eastern Ohio along Interstate 70 to southwest Pennsylvania, and extended south to the Mason Dixon line, and into Garrett county Maryland. North of this band heavy snow of 6 to 7 inches fell from New Philadelphia, Oh to Pittsburgh. Lighter snows of 3 to 6 inches fell from north of Pittsburgh to Interstate 80, and a small amount of freezing rain fell across portions of northern West Virginia.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level low pressure system moved across the Upper Mississippi Valley toward the Great Lakes on Friday, February 24.  An associated surface low that tracked up the Ohio Valley pushed a cold front through the Lower Mississippi Valley and into the Deep South.  Along and ahead of this front, several strong to severe thunderstorms developed in west central Georgia on Friday morning.  Scattered reports of large hail and wind damage were received as these storms moved across northern portions of central Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Greene County 911 Center reported that a few power lines were blown down along Willow Run Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The mid-level low across the Southeast Coast drifted into south Georgia on the 18th, stalled, and began to dissipate.  This continued to bring tropical moisture into the area.  Much like the past couple of days, numerous thunderstorms developed during the afternoon but without the influence of the surface trough from the 17th that had dissipated, fewer storms were able to reach severe levels.  Those that did occurred over north Georgia and resulted in reports of wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Murray County 911 Center reported at least a dozen trees blown down around Chatsworth.

Much like the past couple of days, numerous thunderstorms developed during the afternoon but without the influence of the surface trough from the 17th that had dissipated, fewer storms were able to reach severe levels.  Those that did occurred over north Georgia and resulted in reports of wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Gwinnett County 911 Center reported that seven trees were down including a few at Thrusher Park and Academy Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moderately strong northwesterly flow remained in place over the Ohio Valley and Mid-Atlantic States.  With increasing heat and humidity under the mid-level ridge centered across the Southern Plains, scattered showers and thunderstorms developed during the afternoon of the 25th, mainly across central Georgia.  One thunderstorm was able to reach severe levels with large hail reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Crisp County 911 Center relayed a report from a Sheriff's deputy of hail up to the size of quarters in East Crisp.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level ridge remained in place over the Southern Plains, with weak northwest flow continuing across the Southeast.  Left over outflow boundaries from convection on the 25th helped to focus development on the 26th.  Numerous thunderstorms developed, and several became severe with wind damage reported.  Damage was reported from lightning strikes as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quarter sized hail in Byron.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 1 to 4 inches on December 8th over part of southwest Minnesota was followed by strong northwest winds gusting as high as 54 mph over more of the area on December 9th. The combination of winds, and loose snow cover from the previous day and earlier days, produced blizzard conditions on December 9th, reducing visibilities to near zero over large areas. Travel was curtailed or stopped, and business were closed for part of this weekend storm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Northwest winds gusting to 50 mph and loose snow cover combined to lower visibilities to near zero in blowing snow over much of the area. Travel was brought to a standstill and businesses were closed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A band of snow produced accumulations of 2 to 6 inches near Interstate 90 in southwest Minnesota during the morning and early afternoon of December 18th. Winds during the snowfall were light.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow accumulated 2 to 5 inches, with 5 inches reported at Luverne.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A band of snow produced accumulations of 2 to 6 inches near Interstate 90 in southwest Minnesota during the morning and early afternoon of December 18th. Winds during the snowfall were light.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches, with 3 inches reported at Adrian and Worthington.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm that brought blizzard conditions to portions of Wisconsin and Minnesota and severe weather to portions of the Tennessee River Valley on February 29th weakened as it moved across the Northeast on March 1st.||There were two rounds of snowfall that moved across the North Country, the first during the evening and overnight of February 29th and the second during the daylight hours of March 1st. The first round delivered widespread 1-3 inches across much of Vermont with 6 to 10 inches along the east slopes of the central and southern Green Mountains. The second round delivered another 1-3 inches with some areas that witnessed 3 to 5 inches additional accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began during the evening hours of February 29th and continued through March 1st. Snowfall accumulations are included in March storm data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold and fast-moving system moved across the northern Pacific and into California on the 26th. The system brought a relatively quick period of heavy snow to the northern Sierra from the afternoon of the 25th through the morning of the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A widespread 8 to 13 inches of snow fell in the Lake Tahoe Basin east of highway 89 with this system. For areas along and west of highway 89, 15 to 20 inches of snow fell.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold and fast-moving system moved across the northern Pacific and into Nevada on the 26th. The system brought a relatively quick period of heavy snow to the Lake Tahoe area, with some snow spreading into the western Great Basin from the afternoon of the 25th through the morning of the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A widespread 12 to 18 inches of snow fell with this system.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold and fast-moving system moved across the northern Pacific and into Nevada on the 26th. The system brought a relatively quick period of heavy snow to the Lake Tahoe area, with some snow spreading into the western Great Basin from the afternoon of the 25th through the morning of the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A widespread 1 to 3 inches of snow fell with this system. However, some areas in the foothills and between Washoe Valley and Carson City received 4 to 7 inches of snow. Some of the heavier snow totals may have been enhanced by lake effect snow off of Lake Tahoe, especially in the early morning hours of the 26th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold and fast-moving system moved across the northern Pacific and into California on the 26th. The system brought a relatively quick period of heavy snow to the northern Sierra from the afternoon of the 25th through the morning of the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Along and east of highway 395, 4 to 8 inches (locally to 9 inches) of snow fell with this system. For areas west of highway 395, one to 2 feet of snow fell with local amounts up to 29 inches near Mammoth Mountain.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of December. December brought a small amount of moisture in the form of some snow during the middle part of the month, and again at the very end of the month. Although some moisture did arrive to the area, the drought persisted through the month with D2 to D3 conditions continuing through the month, and into January.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought persisted across Republic County during the month of December. Although some moisture arrived to the area in the form of snow during the latter half of the month D2 conditions continued into January.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of severe thunderstorms developed over eastern Oklahoma during the early evening hours of the 19th as a cold front moved into the region from the west. The thunderstorms moved rapidly eastward into Arkansas, producing damaging wind, large hail, and a tornado across west central Arkansas.

An area of low pressure tracking from Arkansas to West Virginia brought heavy snow to southeast Illinois during the morning of December 26th.  The heaviest snow and blizzard conditions occurred from Lawrence County southeastward into the Ohio River Valley.  Further north across Crawford and Richland counties, the snow was a bit lighter and the winds were not quite as strong.  Six to eight inches of snow fell along and southeast of a Hutsonville to Olney line.  Strong winds of 25 to 30 mph created extensive drifting across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow and strong winds impacted Crawford County during the morning of December 26th.  Between 6 and 9 inches of snow fell across the county, including 6.5 inches 1 mile east of Trimble and 9.0 inches in Palestine.  Sustained winds of 25 to 30 mph created extensive blowing and drifting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure tracking from Arkansas to West Virginia brought heavy snow to southeast Illinois during the morning of December 26th. The heaviest snow and blizzard conditions occurred from Lawrence County southeastward into the Ohio River Valley. Further north across Jasper County, the snow was a bit lighter and the winds were not quite as strong. Three to six inches of snow fell across the county, including 4.1 inches 3 miles southwest of Hidalgo.  Strong winds of 25 to 30 mph created extensive drifting.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three to six inches of snow accumulated across Jasper County during the morning of December 26th.  Strong winds of 25 to 30 mph created considerable blowing and drifting of the snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong low pressure was located over New England.  A tight pressure gradient was located across the Mid Atlantic region that led to strong northwest winds to mix down to the surface especially higher elevations like the Allegany Front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts were estimated around 59 mph in Shenandoah National Park.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts were estimated around 59 mph in Shenandoah National Park.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The passage of a potent upper level trough just north of the region resulted in high winds in the Guadalupe Mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: McDonald Observatory had strong westerly winds as an upper trough passed by to the north of the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A passing upper level trough just north of the region resulted in high winds in portions of the Guadalupe Mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A passing upper level trough imparted strong winds to portions of the Guadalupe Mountains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong north Pacific storm south of the Alaska Peninsula produced snow and strong wind across the Alaska Peninsula to the Pribilof Islands that resulted in blizzard conditions.
A strong north Pacific storm south of the Alaska Peninsula produced snow and strong wind across the Alaska Peninsula to the Pribilof Islands that resulted in blizzard conditions.
A low in Prince William Sound produced strong wind and snow through the Thompson Pass area resulting in blizzard conditions.

A storm that moved across the Alaska Peninsula into Bristol Bay pushed a front to the North Gulf Coast. Strong wind and snow in advance of this front produced blizzard conditions in Portage Valley and Thompson Pass.

A large intense north Pacific storm moved into the eastern Bering Sea the weekend of February 25th. This storm produced heavy snow and blizzard conditions across much of south central Alaska and blizzard conditions along the Bering Sea coast and across the Pribilof Islands.

A weak low pressure system moved southeast of southern New England, bringing snow to much of southern New England.  While most of the area received at least an inch of snow, a mesoscale band set up along the south coast of Massachusetts and Rhode Island resulting in incredible snowfall rates.  Eight to twelve inches of snow fell along the coast with five to eight inches falling on Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur Radio operator reported 2 to 4 inches of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of strong to severe storms raced across the Missouri Ozarks and produced several reports of severe winds and wind damage. There was a weak tornado that spun up along the squall line.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Water was running over the road at the intersection of Scenic and Cardinal Streets. The water was up to a foot deep.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As had been the case for a few days, the Southeast states remained on the northern periphery of weak upper level ridging on the 15th.  Ample moisture and warm temperatures, very summer-like in nature, allowed for enough instability to produce scattered thunderstorms especially across north Georgia.  A few of these thunderstorms were able to reach severe levels, with scattered reports of large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported hail that lasted for at least 20 minutes in the area of Burnt Hickory Ridge Estates, northeast toward Harmony Grove Church Road.  The hail started as pea-size and grew to nickel-size by around 5:25 PM EDT.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported that nickel-sized hail occurred at a location off Post Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold air mass was gradually retreating from Arkansas on the 13th, but precipitation moved in from the west before the cold air could exit. In most parts of Arkansas, precipitation began as snow. Then, as warmer air moved in during the day, the snow changed to a mixture of sleet and freezing rain. This occurred during the morning in southern and central sections, and during the afternoon in the north. Finally, the wintry mix changed over to rain as warmer air continued to invade the state. This changeover occurred during the morning in the south, around midday in central sections, and during the afternoon or early evening in the north. Snowfall totals over the southern half of the state were well less than an inch. Over the northern half, most snow accumulations were in the 1 to 3 inch range. However, totals to 4 inches were reported in the higher elevations of Newton County south of Jasper, and in northern Baxter County. Freezing rain amounts ranged from a trace to around .10 inch.

A persistent and moist westerly flow with embedded disturbances resulted in heavy snow for much of western Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals of around 12 inches were measured above the 8000 foot level. Additionally, wind gusts of 25 to 40 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent and moist westerly flow with embedded disturbances resulted in heavy snow for much of western Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals of 5 to 7 inches were measured across the western portion of the area, while 3 to 5 inches were measured across the eastern portion of the area. Additionally, wind gusts of 20 to 30 mph produced localized blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent and moist westerly flow with embedded disturbances resulted in heavy snow for much of western Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals of 5 to 8 inches were measured across the area. Additionally, wind gusts of 20 to 35 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent and moist westerly flow with embedded disturbances resulted in heavy snow for much of western Colorado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals of around 12 inches were measured above the 8000 foot level. Additionally, wind gusts of 20 to 40 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorms produced heavy rain, strong winds, and lightning in Skull Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind from a thunderstorm broke a branch out of a tree and it fell on power wires and knocked out power.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorms produced heavy rain, strong winds, and lightning in Skull Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck a power pole and the pole caught fire.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms caused heavy rain in Payson and minor flooding issues.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 1 and 1.32 inches of rain fell in an hour in and around Payson. Flooding was reported everywhere. The worst was Forest Drive with two feet of water on the road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced heavy rain and street flooding in Dewey-Humbolt.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain (2.10 inches) fell in Dewey-Humbolt. The intersection of Agua Fria and Prescott Street was close for a while due to high water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms caused heavy rain (0.90 inches in 40 minutes), street flooding, and debris on roadways.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Whiteriver Police reported 0.90 inches of rain in 40 minutes and debris on Route 73.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms caused heavy rain and street flooding in Tuba City.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused street flooding in Tuba City with water entering homes. Highway 89 had water and debris on the roadway. Water was flowing in Moenkpi Wash.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought continued to intensify and expand across parts of central and northeast South Dakota through October, resulting in severe to exceptional drought conditions. Many locations continued the trend of recording well below normal precipitation totals for the month. Exceptional drought conditions expanded into Stanley, Jones and southern Lyman counties. Extreme drought conditions spread into southern Dewey, Sully, Hughes, Lyman, Jones, southwest Hyde, Hamlin, Codington, Grant and Deuel counties. Severe drought conditions spread into Corson, Dewey, northwest Hyde, Hand, Faulk, Edmunds, McPherson, Brown, eastern Clark and southern Roberts counties.

Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, and as a result of this shortcoming of rain Pottawatomie County experienced a persistence in drought conditions as the county began and ended the month in D3 (extreme) drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused debris to flow across Interstate 17 south of Sunset Rest Area. The road was closed after the debris punctured tires on several vehicles.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain from a thunderstorm washed debris across Interstate 17. The water and debris were about four inches deep. The road was closed after several vehicles punctured tires on the debris. The road opened after the flow stopped and the roadway was cleared.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was seen from the community of Rough Rock.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was seen form the community of Rough Rock.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced heavy rain in the Paria River Basin in Utah. The water flowed southeast into Arizona and caused flash flooding in the Paria River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A river gage in Paria Canyon measured a four foot rise in less than 30 minutes on the Paria River.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain from thunderstorms caused flash flooding and closed Highway 180 north of Alpine until debris could be cleared from the road.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain fell for 30 minutes northwest of Alpine. Three feet of water covered a country road. Highway 180 was also closed until the water receded and the debris was cleared.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain from thunderstorms caused flash flooding, mud, and rock slides over the Young Heber Road.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain over the Fire area caused a mud and rock slide over Road 512 (Heber-Young Road). Road crews were called to clear the mud and debris from the road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, despite this shortcoming of rain Republic County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought.

Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of upper level disturbances moved through the Southeast from the 22nd into the 23rd, rotating around the mid-level low pressure system located near the Great Lakes.  These disturbances combined with increasing low level moisture and moderate instability as a result of southerly flow around a surface high located in the western Atlantic.  Strong to severe thunderstorms moved into northwest Georgia from northeast Alabama on Wednesday evening, and moved across north Georgia through midnight.  An EF-1 tornado touched down in Floyd County just east of Rome.  Isolated reports of large hail were received as the storms moved across north Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Madison County 911 Center relayed a first-responder report of nickel to quarter-sized hail in the Seagraves Mill Road area near the Madison/Jackson County Line.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Jackson County 911 Center reported that nickel to quarter size hail fell from Hoschton to Jefferson between 11:50 PM and midnight.  Additional reports of heavy rain and large hail were received from the public through this area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface trough stretching from the Carolinas to east central Georgia interacted with an upper low moving across the Deep South on the afternoon of May 22.  Scattered thunderstorms developed, with several becoming strong.  Isolated storms became severe across central Georgia, with large hail and damaging winds reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Toombs County 911 Center reported that three trees were blown down along Highway 147 in Southeastern Toombs County.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported that nine trees were blown down near a residence in southern Toombs County.  Tin roofs were pulled off outbuildings.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary was the focus for scattered severe thunderstorms across portions of western Pennsylvania. A slow moving thunderstorm produced isolated flash flooding over Garrett county Maryland.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported several trees down near Ligonier.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management reported Spring Lick Road washed out by flash flooding. Trees along roadway washed out blocking road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated thunderstorms developed along a stalled frontal boundary during the early morning hours.

Subtropical moisture moving into the region ahead of a strong warm front clashed with modified arctic air in the lower-levels.  This resulted in a complexity of precipitation types with heavy snow experienced near the Canadian border and mix of light snow and freezing rain to the south, largely within the Spokane area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to six inches of snow was reported in the communities of Republic and Boyds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: D3 drought conditions (extreme) continued across all of southeast Alabama through the month of January and into February.  An area of D4 (exceptional) drought conditions developed across portions of Henry and northern Dale counties on January 17th and continued into February.

D3 drought conditions (extreme) continued across all of southeast Alabama through the month of January and into February.  An area of D4 (exceptional) drought conditions developed across portions of Henry and northern Dale counties on January 17th and continued into February.

A mid-level low pressure system moved across the Upper Mississippi Valley toward the Great Lakes on Friday, February 24.  An associated surface low that tracked up the Ohio Valley pushed a cold front through the Lower Mississippi Valley and into the Deep South.  Along and ahead of this front, several strong to severe thunderstorms developed in west central Georgia on Friday morning.  Scattered reports of large hail and wind damage were received as these storms moved across northern portions of central Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Warren County Emergency Manager reported that a couple of trees were blown down in Norwood and a few trees were blown down in Camak.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry high pressure remained in place across the area on the 25th.  While relative humidities dropped below 25 percent during the afternoon of the 25th, 10-hour fuel moistures remained too high for fire danger conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The National Forest Service reported that a human-caused fire labeled South Dicks Assist burned 13.5 acres and resulted in $1,500 in damages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front and a shortwave aloft pushed into the state during the evening of May 31st.  Numerous thunderstorms developed across the area, and several thunderstorms became severe.  Most of the severe reports consisted of downed trees, but there were a couple of large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Upson County 911 Center reported that several trees were blown down in Thomaston near Highway 19.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid-level ridge remained in place over the Southern Plains, with weak northwest flow continuing across the Southeast.  Left over outflow boundaries from convection on the 25th helped to focus development on the 26th.  Numerous thunderstorms developed, and several became severe with wind damage reported.  Damage was reported from lightning strikes as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Broadcast Media relayed a report of a gas station awning downed by strong winds.  The awning only had two columns and was blown over, with most damage occurring because of the canopy hitting the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm that brought blizzard conditions to portions of Wisconsin and Minnesota and severe weather to portions of the Tennessee River Valley on February 29th weakened as it moved across the Northeast on March 1st.||There were two rounds of snowfall that moved across the North Country, the first during the evening and overnight of February 29th and the second during the daylight hours of March 1st. The first round delivered widespread 1-3 inches across much of Vermont with 6 to 10 inches along the east slopes of the central and southern Green Mountains. The second round delivered another 1-3 inches with some areas that witnessed 3 to 5 inches additional accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began during the evening hours of February 29th and continued through March 1st. Snowfall accumulations are included in March storm data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong, cold low pressure remained over the northeast Pacific from the 21st through early on the 24th bringing heavy snow to eastern California.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A widespread two to three feet of snow fell from midday on the 21th through late evening on the 23rd in the Lake Tahoe area, with 4 to 5 feet near the crest and at higher elevations. In addition to heavy snow, winds gusted between 35 and 45 mph at times for periods of significantly reduced visibility.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong, cold low pressure remained over the northeast Pacific from the 21st through early on the 24th bringing heavy snow to eastern California.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two to 4 feet of snow, highest at the immediate Sierra crest, fell west of highway 395 from the evening of the 21st through early morning on the 24th. Near and east of highway 395, 1 to 2 feet of snow fell as far south as Mammoth Lakes (only 9 inches at Crowley Lake). In addition to heavy snow, winds gusted to between 35 and 50 mph at times along highway 395.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure tracking through the Tennessee River Valley spread snow as far north as southeast Illinois.  Accumulations of 6 to 7 inches occurred across Lawrence County, with lighter amounts noted further north toward the I-70 corridor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow spread across Lawrence County during the evening of December 28th, then tapered off an came to an end by the early morning of the 29th.  Total accumulations were generally 6 to 7 inches across the county, including 7.0 inches measured by the Lawrenceville Cooperative Weather Observer.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved across the Appalachians southeast of the Upper Ohio Valley and produce a mixed bag of heavy freezing rain, sleet and heavy snow across parts of the region. Freezing rain accumulations from one quarter to over one half inch occurred across eastern Ohio along Interstate 70 to southwest Pennsylvania, and extended south to the Mason Dixon line, and into Garrett county Maryland. North of this band heavy snow of 6 to 7 inches fell from New Philadelphia, Oh to Pittsburgh. Lighter snows of 3 to 6 inches fell from north of Pittsburgh to Interstate 80, and a small amount of freezing rain fell across portions of northern West Virginia.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As had been the case for a few days, the Southeast states remained on the northern periphery of weak upper level ridging on the 15th.  Ample moisture and warm temperatures, very summer-like in nature, allowed for enough instability to produce scattered thunderstorms especially across north Georgia.  A few of these thunderstorms were able to reach severe levels, with scattered reports of large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quart-sized hail on Highway 278 about three miles west of Rockmart.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front and a shortwave aloft pushed into the state during the evening of May 31st.  Numerous thunderstorms developed across the area, and several thunderstorms became severe.  Most of the severe reports consisted of downed trees, but there were a couple of large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The White County Emergency Manager reported that a half dozen trees were blown down in a yard along Kellum Valley Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches, with 4 inches reported at Jackson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm that brought blizzard conditions to portions of Wisconsin and Minnesota and severe weather to portions of the Tennessee River Valley on February 29th weakened as it moved across the Northeast on March 1st.||There were two rounds of snowfall that moved across the North Country, the first during the evening and overnight of February 29th and the second during the daylight hours of March 1st. The first round delivered widespread 1-3 inches across much of Vermont with 6 to 10 inches along the east slopes of the central and southern Green Mountains. The second round delivered another 1-3 inches with some areas that witnessed 3 to 5 inches additional accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began during the evening hours of February 29th and continued through March 1st. Snowfall accumulations are included in March storm data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold and fast-moving system moved across the northern Pacific and into Nevada on the 26th. The system brought a relatively quick period of heavy snow to the Lake Tahoe area, with some snow spreading into the western Great Basin from the afternoon of the 25th through the morning of the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One to three inches of snow (locally to 4 inches in Lovelock) fell from the afternoon of the 25th through early morning on the 26th, mainly north of highway 50 as evidenced by  the KRGX radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large west to northwest swell generated high surf on the 1st and 2nd, mainly along west-facing beaches of Orange and San Diego County. Surf heights peaked on the 1st and gradually decreased into the 3rd. Tidal swings of over 6 feet occurred between the highest morning high tides and lowest afternoon low tides. The highest surf occurred in San Diego County with heights averaging 5-8 feet and sets to 13 feet at times. No damage was observed, though the Ocean Beach Pier was closed for a time due to the high surf.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Huntington Beach lifeguards reported surf of 7 to 8 feet.

Path length was approximately 1.5 miles and path width was 20 yards. Maximum winds were estimated at 70 mph.

The drought continued to intensify and expand across parts of central and northeast South Dakota through October, resulting in severe to exceptional drought conditions. Many locations continued the trend of recording well below normal precipitation totals for the month. Exceptional drought conditions expanded into Stanley, Jones and southern Lyman counties. Extreme drought conditions spread into southern Dewey, Sully, Hughes, Lyman, Jones, southwest Hyde, Hamlin, Codington, Grant and Deuel counties. Severe drought conditions spread into Corson, Dewey, northwest Hyde, Hand, Faulk, Edmunds, McPherson, Brown, eastern Clark and southern Roberts counties.

The drought continued to intensify and expand across Big Stone and Traverse counties in west central Minnesota. Extreme drought conditions moved into extreme southeast Big Stone county, while severe drought conditions lifted into the southern third of Traverse county.

CZ_NAME: LITTLE COLORADO RIVER VALLEY IN NAVAJO COUNTY
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep and cold winter storm system appoaching Arizona brought strong winds and blowing dust to areas northeast of major terrain features such as the Mogollon Rim and San Fransisco Peaks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Winslow ASOS reported less than 3 miles visibility in blowing dust for over two hours. A trained spotter one mile east of Winslow reported one mile visibility in blowing dust at 1255 PM.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front pushed across the Mid South during the evening hours of October 14, 2012. Isolated to scattered showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the front across mainly Northeast Mississippi. One storm intensified and became severe across Monroe County and produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Straight line winds removed a roof from a home on Highway 45 north of Aberdeen. Several trees were knocked down on Coontail Road. A car was knocked off the road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms dropped heavy rain over the area that was burned by the Schultz Fire (2010) causing water to flow into the neighborhood below.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain over the Schultz Fire area washed out a couple of driveways and a portion of Brandis Way.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front moving through southern middle Tennessee spawned a broken line of strong to isolated severe storms. One storm became severe and produced a small area of straight line thunderstorm wind damage in Lincoln county, Tennessee.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew in a large garage door and ripped off a portion of a metal roof from a small hangar at a residence near Ardmore Highway 110 just east of Taft. Winds were estimated to be around 70 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm produced minor lightning damage at a residence in Limestone County, AL.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck a home in the Indian Trace neighborhood near Athens and produced minor damage to the residence.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level disturbance and associated cold front moved through the Mid-South during the evening hours of October 17, 2012. The cold front interacted with a moist and unstable airmass in place over the region and a line of showers and thunderstorms developed over Eastern Arkansas and then swept east across the Mid-South. Strong winds aloft aided in the development of the line of thunderstorms some of which became severe and produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Straight line winds knocked trees down on County Road 300 near Hornor.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Straight line winds blew large billboards apart and broke large plexiglass signs in Kennett. Minor roof damage occurred to several buildings. Carports and a few portable buildings were blown over as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, despite this shortcoming of rain Riley County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level disturbance interacting with an approaching cold front triggered scattered thunderstorms across north-central Illinois during the late afternoon and evening of June 16th.  A few of the storms became severe, producing spotty wind damage and large hail.  In addition, lightning caused a house fire in Dunlap in Peoria County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave moved across northern Alabama during the late morning hours on May 29, pushing into northwest Georgia during the evening.  Meanwhile the remnants of Tropical Storm Beryl moved across southeast Georgia.  Instability was able to increase around the periphery of Beryl where cloud cover was not as thick, and as the shortwave moved into the state, isolated severe thunderstorms developed.  Most of the reports consisted of downed trees, but there was one report of severe hail as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Chattooga County Emergency Management and the 911 Center reported that a few trees were downed in the western portion of the county, including on State Line Road, Georgia Highway 337 and Reed Street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The upper shortwave that pushed through the Southern Appalachians on the 16th, inducing the lee side trough, remained a factor in thunderstorm development on the 17th.  Additionally, a mid-level low off the Southeast Coast began moving onshore, bringing additional moisture to the area.  Numerous thunderstorms developed during the day, and several of them became severe with mostly wind damage, but a few large hail reports as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Meriwether County 911 Center reported that several trees were blown down in the Gay area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system translated from the Pacific Northwest across the Southern Rockies and into the Southern Plains from the 23rd through the 25th. Rain began across west central Arkansas during the early morning hours of the 25th as this system approached and then transitioned to light freezing rain and a little sleet. The precipitation changed over to snow during the early afternoon of the 25th and fell heavily for several hours before tapering off late in the evening. A swath of heavy snow from four to six inches occurred across west central Arkansas.

A line of severe thunderstorms developed over eastern Oklahoma during the early evening hours of the 19th as a cold front moved into the region from the west. The thunderstorms moved rapidly eastward, producing damaging wind and large hail across mainly southeastern Oklahoma.

A line of severe thunderstorms developed over eastern Oklahoma during the early evening hours of the 19th as a cold front moved into the region from the west. The thunderstorms moved rapidly eastward into Arkansas, producing damaging wind, large hail, and a tornado across west central Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado developed near Highway 96 north of Union Road where it damaged a permanent home and trees. It moved northeast uprooting or snapping numerous hardwood and softwood trees and damaging chicken houses and outbuildings. The tornado damaged the sides and roof of a fire station on County Road 68, tore the roof off a double wide mobile home north of County Road 68, then destroyed a double wide mobile home and tore the roofs off of three chicken houses before moving into a wooded area. Based on this damage, maximum estimated wind in the tornado was 100 to 110 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of severe thunderstorms developed over eastern Oklahoma during the early evening hours of the 19th as a cold front moved into the region from the west. The thunderstorms moved rapidly eastward, producing damaging wind and large hail across mainly southeastern Oklahoma.

A low pressure system moved across the Appalachians southeast of the Upper Ohio Valley and produce a mixed bag of heavy freezing rain, sleet and heavy snow across parts of the region. Freezing rain accumulations from one quarter to over one half inch occurred across eastern Ohio along Interstate 70 to southwest Pennsylvania, and extended south to the Mason Dixon line, and into Garrett county Maryland. North of this band heavy snow of 6 to 7 inches fell from New Philadelphia, Oh to Pittsburgh. Lighter snows of 3 to 6 inches fell from north of Pittsburgh to Interstate 80, and a small amount of freezing rain fell across portions of northern West Virginia.

Subtropical Storm Beryl continued to spin off the Southeast Coast, with a landfall expected near the Georgia/Florida border late in the day.  Scattered showers with isolated thunderstorms developed across the state during the day as winds increased due to the strengthening pressure gradient.  Because of the recent dry spell, fuel moistures were very low, but with increasing moisture as a result of Beryl, relative humidities remained just over critical thresholds for dangerous fire weather conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The National Forest Service reported that a wildfire of unknown cause labeled Dial Pullover burned 0.1 acres and resulted in $500 in damages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions continued over all of southeast South Dakota in December. Although precipitation was generally normal to above normal...the amount of excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. The effects of the drought on farmers and ranchers continued, with the poor condition of winter wheat, and the low stock of winter feed for livestock. Hunting was also affected according to conservation officers, with low pheasant numbers, and disease in the deer population. There were few remaining water restrictions given the much lower water usage compared with the summer and fall, but the low soil moisture levels presented a bleak outlook for the next spring and summer without a very significant increase in precipitation over the winter. Drought was generally listed as continued severe to extreme for the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Long term dry soil conditions continued, despite normal to above normal precipitation, as the excess over the low winter normals was not enough to relieve the dry conditions. Aside from the effects on winter wheat and available winter livestock feed, hunting was hampered due to reduced pheasant population and disease in the deer population. The future effect of the lack of soil moisture on next spring and summer's farming was feared if the dryness were to continue. Otherwise, few new effects of the drought were noted during the month due to the seasonally low water usage and need.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold air mass was gradually retreating from Arkansas on the 13th, but precipitation moved in from the west before the cold air could exit. In most parts of Arkansas, precipitation began as snow. Then, as warmer air moved in during the day, the snow changed to a mixture of sleet and freezing rain. This occurred during the morning in southern and central sections, and during the afternoon in the north. Finally, the wintry mix changed over to rain as warmer air continued to invade the state. This changeover occurred during the morning in the south, around midday in central sections, and during the afternoon or early evening in the north. Snowfall totals over the southern half of the state were well less than an inch. Over the northern half, most snow accumulations were in the 1 to 3 inch range. However, totals to 4 inches were reported in the higher elevations of Newton County south of Jasper, and in northern Baxter County. Freezing rain amounts ranged from a trace to around .10 inch.

There were no reports of injuries or fatalities, however damage was reported across the south central Texas Panhandle.

A deepening low pressure system tracking northeast through the Ohio Valley brought accumulating snow and blowing snow to northern Indiana on December 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow fell on December 26th, with total snow accumulations generally ranging between 3 and 5 inches across the county. The falling snow combined with wind gusts in excess of 30 mph reduced visibilities to less than a quarter of a mile at times. Temperatures were in the upper 20s as the snow fell which allowed roads to become snow covered and slick. This resulted in slide-offs and accidents across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A more active weather pattern occurred during the month of October with several rounds of appreciable rainfall. Drought conditions continued to slowly improve over portions of extreme southeastern Kansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The U.S Drought Monitor continued to report Severe Drought (D2) to Extreme Drought (D3) throughout the month of October. The COOP station near Walnut reported 2.22 of rainfall for the month of October. The COOP station near Pittsburg reported 2.02 of rainfall for the month of October. This is a continuation of the drought that began across the region in June. The loss and damage estimates will be included in August's storm data section for the entire drought event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex low pressure system entering the Ohio Valley on December 28th transferred its energy to a secondary low along the North Carolina coast on the 29th. The secondary low intensifed into a nor'easter off the Mid Atlantic and New England coasts later on the 29th, and brought heavy snow to most of southern Connecticut.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters and state DOT reported snowfall of 2 to nearly 6 inches. The highest snowfall amount of 5.8 inches was at New Canaan.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters and state DOT measured between 5 and 11 inches of snowfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance moved through north Georgia during the morning of April 26.  Additional upper level disturbances pushed through the Southeast during the evening and overnight hours on the 26th.  Also, an area of surface low pressure moving through the Ohio Valley pushed a cold front into north Georgia late on Thursday.  Two waves of scattered thunderstorms developed, one in the morning and again in the early evening.  With each wave, one thunderstorm was able to reach severe levels, with both severe thunderstorms occurring in the town of Hiawassee in Towns county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported quarter sized hail in Hiawassee.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level disturbance and associated cold front moved through the Mid-South during the evening hours of October 17, 2012. The cold front interacted with a moist and unstable airmass in place over the region and a line of showers and thunderstorms developed over Eastern Arkansas and then swept east across the Mid-South. Strong winds aloft aided in the development of the line of thunderstorms some of which became severe and produced large hail and damaging winds.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail fell at the intersection of Byhalia Road and Craft Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level disturbance interacting with an approaching cold front triggered scattered thunderstorms across north-central Illinois during the late afternoon and evening of June 16th.  A few of the storms became severe, producing spotty wind damage and large hail.  In addition, lightning caused a house fire in Dunlap in Peoria County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A lightning strike set a house on fire on Pauli Road in Dunlap.  The house burned to the ground and was a total loss.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level disturbance interacting with an approaching cold front triggered scattered thunderstorms across north-central Illinois during the late afternoon and evening of June 16th.  A few of the storms became severe, producing spotty wind damage and large hail.  In addition, lightning caused a house fire in Dunlap in Peoria County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level disturbance and associated cold front moved through the Mid-South during the evening hours of October 17, 2012. The cold front interacted with a moist and unstable airmass in place over the region and a line of showers and thunderstorms developed over Eastern Arkansas and then swept east across the Mid-South. Strong winds aloft aided in the development of the line of thunderstorms some of which became severe and produced large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail fell near the intersection of Deadfall and McQuiston Roads near Idaville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level disturbance and associated cold front moved through the Mid-South during the evening hours of October 17, 2012. Several trees were knocked down in the area as well with a few of them falling on houses. A car was turned around by the winds on Highway 51 near the intersection of Arkabutla Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions continued across all of the central plains through the month of October. Drought monitor for the central plains indicated that some improvement in the drought conditions were experienced across all of northeast Kansas. The month started with a majority of the area in D3 (extreme) drought, but ended with a large portion of the area being downgraded to D2 (severe) drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions persisted across northeast, north central, and east central Kansas in October. Below normal precipitation occurred in October, however, despite this shortcoming of rain Wabaunsee County actually saw some slight improvement in drought conditions as the county ended the month in D2 (severe) to D3 (extreme) drought.

A deep upper level trough across the western plains lifted north and east towards the region during the afternoon and overnight hours of April 3rd and morning hours of April 4th. Deep layer shear supported the development of super cell thunderstorms across North Central Texas during the afternoon hours of April 3rd and these storms moved into the region, producing strong and damaging wind gusts, large hail and a few tornadoes across most of the region.

Scattered to numerous showers and thunderstorms developed along and ahead of a cold front across much of East Texas during the morning and afternoon of April 20th. While surface based instability was weak, very steep lapse rates aloft coupled with increasing forcing aloft resulted in isolated severe thunderstorms over portions of East Texas, which resulted in several reports of large hail. The severe threat shifted southward across East Texas from morning to afternoon, ending across Deep East Texas around mid afternoon as the air mass stabilized from widespread areas of showers with embedded thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail was reported two miles south of Alto, Texas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An MCS developed across Southeast Texas during the overnight and early morning hours of April 2nd. This upper level disturbance rounded the base of an upper level trough across Southeast Texas and moved northeastward into Northeast Texas, Northern Louisiana and Southern Arkansas during the late morning and afternoon hours of April 2nd. The atmosphere ahead of this line of thunderstorms became very unstable by late morning with CAPE values approaching 4000 J/Kg. Very steep lapse rates were also present such that large hail and damaging thunderstorm wind gusts were the primary threat with these storms. Widespread tree damage was reported across all of Northeast Texas, Northern Louisiana and Southern Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed on a home on Stratmore Drive.
